  "prompt": "What happens to the photons when I switch off the light?",
  "response": "When you switch off the light, the photons that were being emitted by the light source are no longer produced. Photons are the elementary particles responsible for carrying electromagnetic energy, including visible light. Once the light source is off, the emission of new photons stops immediately.\n\nAs for the photons already emitted before switching off the light, they continue to travel away from the light source at the speed of light until they are absorbed or scattered by objects or surfaces in their path. This could include being absorbed by walls, furniture, or even the air molecules themselves. Once absorbed, the energy of the photons is typically converted into other forms of energy, such as heat. Thus, the photons themselves effectively cease to exist as distinct particles after absorption.",
